the AccountInfo.

entry.title: AppRescue feature to be made default
entry.content:
This is per the positive impact from the ChromeOSARCVMAppRescue

finch experiment. Specifically:



Arc.App.LowMemoryKills.OnlyArc.Pressure.PerceptibleCount10Minutes

got small improvements across all groups (see bottom link).



Overview, low-ram devices, lots of improvement, crashes reduced:

https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/variations?sid=8861db61406b86f3812bd72c29ea382b



Overview, other devices, no regression, small improvements:

https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/variations?sid=5401a3fd4757d7103ab9f3da2a621bc0



The small memory increase on low-RAM devices is Chrome making

good use of the extra RAM it gets, as evidenced by a sharp reduction

of ARCVM footprint for the users in most dire need.

Users who did not have that much memory need have a small ARCVM increase.



https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/variations?sid=bdae55e2fae7f1244c702f2f743c2847



Additionally, per discussion with Data team, went through the

process from go/cros-exp-stability-process , and finally got

approval from stability committee (jhorwich@) and eng lead (arthurhsu@).

See details in http://go/launch-app-rescue-analysys



Bug: b:241321277

entry.title: All system DNS resolution runs on a threadpool at USER_BLOCKING pri
entry.content:
System DNS resolution was being run at USER_VISIBLE task priority.

The definition of USER_BLOCKING includes the loading path, and

system DNS resolution is on the loading path, so it shouldn't

run at a lower priority.



Also, the browser's UI thread was handling requests from the network

service for out-of-process system DNS resolution and then farming

those requests out to the thread pool. There's no reason to deal

with the UI thread contention and so the dispatcher for system DNS

resolution requests will now run on a thread pool sequence at

USER_BLOCKING priority.

entry.title: Remove online signin timestamps from preferences
entry.content:
OfflineSigninLimiter kept signin timestamps in 3 copies: in preferences

separate for saml and non-saml cases and in the Local State for the

login screen logic. The 2 preferences already seem to be redundant

(we only have a single event representing latest online reauth, no

matter whether it was saml or non-saml) and the only reason to have

them on top of the Local State was a different logic on the login and

lock screens.



Per PM recommendation we want to simplify this functionality: online

reauth will reset timers the same on the login and lock screen. This

makes those 2 preferences unnecessary. In this cl we remove the

relevant login, in the following one we will deprecate the prefs

themselves.

entry.title: [Office upload] Show appropriate error message for ODFS Copy/Move flow
entry.content:
Show the appropriate error message for failure in ODFS Copy/Move flow.

ShowIOTaskError was added to find base::File::Error errors and convert

them to an appropriate error notification. The

base::File::Error comes from

- ODFS (cl/541466788)

- or the Copy or Move IO task



ShowReauthenticationOrMoveUploadError was moved to ShowIOTaskError.

There is no need to use GetActions to check if re authentication is

required in ODFS because now the Copy/Move task will fail with

base::File::Error::FILE_ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED (cl/541466788) when re

authentication is required. Previously it would fail with some other

error and a call to GetActions, which always returns ACCESS_DENIED with

re authentication is required, was necessary.



Note: ODFS distinguishes between re authentication required and a

generic authentication error by using ProviderError.ACCESS_DENIED and

ProviderError.SECURITY respectively. Re authentication being required

is a special authentication error that requires a special notification

b/279109210.



New notifications: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1eCaNqapzfcLu2vaGinL7b4p1XK-9gb571iy4Xyxw7Dw/edit?resourcekey=0-vmYxDvtFyJLZ35zuUUnQiA#slide=id.g25283deed79_0_6
